    "excerpt": "This translation of the poem \"Éshet Neürim\" by Elḥanan ben Yitsḥaq of Dampierre (d. 1184) was made by Israel Zangwill and first published in his collection of poetry, <em>Blind Children: Poems</em> (1903), under the title, \"Israel as Bride and as Beggar\" on page 118. (An earlier translation in German was made by Leopold Zunz in <em>Die synagogale Poesie des Mittelalters</em> (1855), p. 249.)  . . .",
    "content": "<table style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" class=\"draggable toggleable-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th id=\"x\" style=\"text-align: right;\">Source (Hebrew)</th>\n<th style=\"text-align: left;\">Rhyming translation (English)</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"heb-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">אֵ</span>שֶׁת נְעוּרִים הָאֲהוּבָה<br />\nאֲשֶׁר אֵרַשְׂתָּ בְּרֹב מֹהַר וְרֹב טוֹבָה<br />\nוְאֵיךְ עַתָּה יוֹשֶׁבֶת עֲלוּבָה<br />\nגְּעוּלָה וּמְאוּסָה וַעֲזוּבָה\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">E</span>rst radiant the Bride adored,<br />\nOn whom rich wedding-gifts are poured,<br />\nShe weeps, sore wounded, ov&#8217;erthrown,<br />\nExiled and outcast, shunned and lone.\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"heb-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">לְ</span>בוּשָׁהּ בַּעֲדִי עֲדָיִים<br />\nאֲשֶׁר הִתְנֵיתָ בִּבְרִית וּבִתְנָאִים<br />\nוְאֵיךְ עַתָּה סוֹבֶבֶת דְּלָתַיִם<br />\nוְשׁוֹכֶבֶת בֵּין שְׁפַתָּיִם\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">L</span>aid all aside her garments fair,<br />\nThe pledges of a bond divine,<br />\nA wandering beggar-woman&#8217;s wear<br />\nIs hers in lieu of raiment fine.\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"heb-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">חֲ</span>בוּשָׁה בְּשֵׁשׁ וּמֶשִׁי כְּלוּלָה<br />\nהִיא הָיְתָה בְּכָל הָאָרֶץ מְהֻלָּלָה<br />\nוְאֵיךְ עַתָּה נֶחְשֶׁבֶת מֵחֻלָּלָה<br />\nלְלַעַג וּלְבֹשֶׁת וְלִקְלָלָה\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">Ch</span>anted hath been in every land<br />\nThe beauty of her crown and zone;<br />\nNow doomed, dethroned, she maketh moan,<br />\nBemocked — a byword — cursed and banned.\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"heb-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">נְ</span>וַת פַּעֲמַיִם בִּנְעָלֶיהָ<br />\nאֲשֶׁר כְּנָפֶיךָ פְּרוּשִׂים עָלֶיהָ<br />\nוְאֵיךְ עַתָּה נִגְּפוּ רַגְלֶיהָ<br />\nעַל הֶהָרִים אַחַר עוֹלָלֶיהָ\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">An</span> airy, joyous step was hers<br />\nBeneath Thy wing. But now she crawls<br />\nAlong and mourns her sons and errs<br />\nAt every step, and, worn out, falls.\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"heb-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">נָ</span>א יוֹשֵׁב הַכְּרוּבִים<br />\nתֵּרֶא בְּכָל זֹאת לֹא פָנְתָה אֶל רְהָבִים<br />\nלֹא עַל פָּרָשִׁים וְלֹא עַל רוֹכְבִים<br />\nכִּי עַל רַחֲמֶיךָ הָרַבִּים\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">An</span>d yet to Thee she clingeth tight.<br />\nVain, vain to her man&#8217;s mortal might<br />\nWhich in a breath to naught is hurled,<br />\nThy smile alone makes up her world.\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<p>This translation of the poem &#8220;Éshet Neürim&#8221; by Elḥanan ben Yitsḥaq of Dampierre (d. 1184) was made by Israel Zangwill and first published in his collection of poetry, <em>Blind Children: Poems</em> (1903), under the title, &#8220;Israel as Bride and as Beggar&#8221; on page 118. (An earlier translation in German was made by Leopold Zunz in <em>Die synagogale Poesie des Mittelalters</em> (1855), p. 249.) </p>\n<h3>Source(s)</h3